            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Priya Sharma sees San Francisco not as a collection of streets, but as a complex circulatory system, and she is one of its principal physicians. Born to Indian immigrants in suburban Michigan, her childhood was defined by the very car-centric culture she now works to evolve. Her father, a methodical engineer, and her mother, a community-focused librarian, instilled in her a blend of systematic thinking and a deep sense of public service. The endless drives of her youth sparked a fascination with a different way of living\u2014one built on proximity and connection.\n\nThis fascination led her to a Master's in Transportation Management at UC Berkeley, a move that felt like a true homecoming. She fell in love with the Bay Area's dynamic energy and the inherent challenge of moving millions of people within its compact geography. Priya began her career as a junior planner, meticulously analyzing traffic flow and advocating for bike lanes when they were still a radical idea. Her defining professional moment came in the early 2000s, when she successfully championed a pedestrian-focused redesign of a congested corridor, a project that became a model for future developments and cemented her reputation as a visionary.\n\nNow, at 54, Priya\u2019s life is a testament to her professional philosophy. She lives in a tastefully minimalist apartment in Hayes Valley, just a 0.8-mile walk from her office. Her days start with a walk to a local cafe for an oat latte and end with policy debates and community meetings. Divorced for over a decade, she maintains a close, long-distance relationship with her son, Anand, a software engineer in Austin. Her social life is a curated circle of fellow civic leaders and old friends, meeting for dinners or catching a performance at the nearby symphony.\n\nPriya\u2019s connection to San Francisco is etched into its very pavement. Every bus-only lane and protected bike path feels like a personal victory. Her ultimate aspiration is to oversee the implementation of a truly integrated, equitable, and climate-resilient mobility network for the city. She dreams of a future where San Francisco is a global leader in sustainable urban living, a legacy she is helping build, one carefully planned step at a time."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nShe recalls the vinyl backseat of her father's station wagon, stuck in traffic on a Michigan highway. She was ten. Outside, the world was a blur of steel and exhaust. She pressed her face to the glass, watching a distant sidewalk, wishing she could be there\u2014walking, free. It wasn\u2019t a desire for escape, but for connection. The hollow feeling of isolation that day became the fuel for her life\u2019s work, a quiet vow to build a world where no one felt so helplessly contained.\n\n2.\nHer first ride on BART into Berkeley in the early '90s was a true awakening. Descending into the SFO station felt like entering a new world. The rumbling train was a vessel of kinetic energy, filled with a vibrant mix of people she\u2019d never see in her suburban town. Emerging into the East Bay sunlight, she felt the city\u2019s pulse for the first time. This wasn't just transit; it was belonging. She knew, with absolute certainty, she was finally home.\n\n3.\nIt was 2003, the morning after her redesigned corridor opened. Before the official ceremony, she walked the new, wider sidewalks alone. A woman pushed a stroller without battling cars; an elderly man sat on a bench where there had only been parking. She felt a profound, almost maternal pride. It wasn't just about traffic flow; it was about creating moments of peace. That quiet observation cemented her conviction that her vision could reshape not just streets, but the human experience within them.\n\n4.\nShe pictures Anand\u2019s small hand clutching a Muni pole, his face alight with wonder as the 21-Hayes trundled past Alamo Square Park. He was seven. She wasn\u2019t just teaching him the bus route; she was showing him the city\u2019s circulatory system, proving how its different parts connected. The memory is bittersweet now that he\u2019s in Austin, a reminder of a bond forged not just in love, but in the shared geography of a city she was helping build for him.\n\n5.\nJust last Tuesday, on her walk to the cafe, she saw a young woman on a scooter glide into the new protected bike lane on her street. Priya had spent three years advocating for that lane. The woman\u2019s ease, her carefree momentum, was a silent, personal victory. At 54, her legacy wasn\u2019t in grand monuments, but in these small, daily acts of freedom she\u2019d fought to make possible. It was a feeling of deep, quiet satisfaction, the city breathing a little easier because of her."
